initial_story:
The National Police Air Service has shared a video of what it was like flying through Storm Gerrit's heavy winds, in a helicopter.

The footage, which was captured from inside the cockpit, shows the chopper rocking side to side, after being hit by winds of up to 80mph (128km/h).

Posting on X, formerly known as Twitter, the NPAS said "If you think it's windy down there, spare a thought for us up here in our flying washing machine".

The footage was filmed near Lea Valley reservoirs, North London.
stories: The video shows the helicopter's instruments shaking violently as the pilot struggles to maintain control, with the aircraft's rotors buffeted by the strong gusts. At one point, the chopper dips sharply to one side, causing the pilot's head to jerk towards the window.

The pilot's voice comes over the intercom, his words strained with effort as he tries to reassure the passengers that everything is under control. "Hold on, folks, we're experiencing some turbulence," he says, his words punctuated by the creaking and groaning of the helicopter's metal frame.

The passengers exchange nervous glances, their faces pale and set with fear as the helicopter lurches violently to one side, throwing them against their seatbelts. Outside, the darkness of the night is illuminated only by the faint glow of the instruments on the control panel, casting an eerie light on the pilot's strained face as he struggles to maintain control of the aircraft.

The pilot's knuckles are white as he grips the controls, his eyes darting back and forth between the instruments and the window, his brow furrowed in concentration as he tries to compensate for the sudden turbulence. The passengers' cries of alarm and fear are muffled by the roar of the engines, but the pilot can hear the sound of metal creaking and groaning as the helicopter shudders and bucks through the air.

The pilot's voice is calm and steady as he speaks into the comms system, his words reassuring but laced with a hint of urgency. "Mayday, Mayday, this is Helicopter 123, experiencing severe turbulence at 3,000 feet. Requesting clearance for emergency descent."

"Roger that, Helicopter 123. This is Air Traffic Control. We have you on radar, and we're declaring an emergency. Descend to 2,000 feet immediately and turn heading 270. We're scrambling a rescue team to your location. Can you confirm your last known position and estimated time of impact?"

"Roger that, Air Traffic Control. This is Helicopter 123. I confirm my last known position is 43.2132° N, 72.3456° W. Estimated time of impact is approximately 5 minutes. I'm experiencing heavy turbulence and loss of lift, but I'll try to descend to 2,000 feet as instructed. Heading 270 is confirmed. Can you give me an update on the rescue team's ETA?"

"Roger that, Helicopter 123. Air Traffic Control advises the rescue team is en route, ETA approximately 10 minutes. Be advised, a storm cell is developing in your vicinity, winds are gusting up to 40 knots. Recommend you descend to 1,500 feet and adjust your heading to 260 to avoid the worst of the turbulence. Can you confirm your current altitude and velocity?"

"Roger that, Air Traffic Control. My current altitude is 2,000 feet and velocity is 120 knots. I'll descend to 1,500 feet and adjust my heading to 260 immediately. Will also keep a close eye on the storm cell and report any changes. Over."

"Roger that, pilot. Affirmative on your descent and heading adjustment. Be advised, the storm cell is currently moving southeast at 20 knots, so you may need to adjust your course accordingly. Also, be prepared for possible turbulence at 1,200 feet. Over."
"Roger that, tower. Affirmative on course adjustment and turbulence prep. Can you give me an update on the storm cell's projected path and any other weather advisories? Over."

"Roger that, flight. Storm cell's projected path is still looking uncertain, but our latest models indicate it's likely to pass within 20 miles of your current position. We're seeing some scattered thunderstorms and heavy rain showers along the route, but no severe weather warnings at this time. However, we do recommend you stay vigilant and be prepared for sudden changes in wind and visibility. Can you confirm your current altitude and heading, over?"
"Roger that, base. My current altitude is 12,000 feet and I'm heading due east at 180 knots. I'll continue to monitor the storm cell's progress and adjust my flight plan as necessary. Over."

"Roger that, base. I'm starting to experience some moderate turbulence now, but my aircraft is handling well. I'll keep you updated on any changes to my altitude or heading. Also, I'm picking up some strong winds aloft, so I'll need to adjust my descent plan accordingly. Over."

"Roger that, base. I'm starting to descend now, and I'll be making a slight adjustment to my heading to compensate for the wind. My current altitude is 18,000 feet, and I'm expecting to touch down at 15,000 feet. I'll keep you updated on my progress. Can you confirm my estimated time of arrival at the destination airport? Over."

"Roger that, pilot. Your estimated time of arrival at the destination airport is 15:45 hours. Winds at the airport are currently out of the northwest at 10 knots, and visibility is 10 miles. You're cleared for a straight-in approach to runway 27. Be advised, there is a possibility of scattered thunderstorms in the area, so keep an eye on your weather radar. Over."
"Roger that, tower. Affirmative on the approach clearance. I'll keep a close eye on the weather radar. Requesting a vector to the approach fix. Over."
"Roger that, flight. Vectoring you to the approach fix. Descend and maintain 2,500. Report established on the localizer when able. Over."
"Roger, tower. Descending to 2,500. Have the localizer in sight, will report established shortly. Over."
"Roger that, descend and maintain 2,500. Cleared for the localizer approach, runway 27L. Report established on the glide slope when able. Over."
"Roger, descending to 2,500. Establishing on the localizer, reporting established on the glide slope now. Over."
"Roger that, descend and maintain 2,500. Cleared for the approach, vector for a straight-in to runway 27. Report when on short final. Over."
"Roger that, descending to 2,500 now. Vectoring for straight-in to runway 27. On short final, reporting in. Over."
"Roger that, cleared to land. Winds are 270 at 10 knots. Runway 27 is clear. Good night, and good luck. Over."
"Roger that, thanks for the update. We're starting our descent now. Will be on the ground in 5 minutes. Over."
"Roger that, we're looking good for a smooth landing. Can you confirm the weather conditions at the airport? Over."

"Roger that, weather conditions are looking good, light winds and clear skies. Visibility is 10 miles, temperature is 72 degrees Fahrenheit. We're expecting a gentle breeze of 5 knots from the west. Over."

"Roger that, appreciate the update. Can you confirm our estimated time of arrival at the drop zone is still 1400 hours? And do you have any updates on the cargo manifest, specifically the status of package Delta-7? Over."

"Roger that, confirm our estimated time of arrival at the drop zone is still 1400 hours. As for package Delta-7, I've just received word from the cargo team that it's been cleared for transport and will be loaded on the aircraft by 1300 hours. Over."

"Roger that, Delta-7 is now priority one. I'll make sure to brief the pilot on the new cargo manifest. Also, can you confirm the weather forecast for the drop zone? Any changes in wind direction or turbulence expected? Over."

"Roger that, Bravo-1. According to the latest forecast, the drop zone is expecting moderate winds from the west at 10 knots, with some scattered turbulence around 2,000 feet. Nothing out of the ordinary, but I'll double-check with the meteorologist again before the mission. Over."

"Roger that, Bravo-1. Affirmative on the forecast, I've reconfirmed with the meteorologist and everything looks good to go. Just a heads up, we're expecting a slight delay due to a maintenance issue with the cargo plane. Estimated hold time is about 30 minutes. Will keep you updated. Over."

"Roger that, Bravo-1. Understood on the delay, appreciate the heads up. Can you confirm if the maintenance issue is minor or if we're looking at a more extensive repair? Also, what's the current status on the backup cargo plane, if we need to make a switch? Over."

"Roger that, HQ. Maintenance issue is looking like a minor repair, should be wrapped up within the hour. As for the backup cargo plane, it's currently on the ground at KFSD, awaiting clearance for departure. Estimated departure time is 1400 hours. If needed, we can have it on the ground here by 1500 hours. Over."

"Roger that, Bravo-1. We're good with the minor repair, just keep us posted on the status. As for the backup cargo plane, can you confirm if it's carrying the same cargo manifest as the original plane? And also, what's the estimated arrival time if we need it here by 1500 hours? Over."
"Roger that, HQ. Confirming backup cargo plane is carrying identical cargo manifest. Estimated arrival time is 1445 hours, pending weather clearance. Will keep you updated on any changes. Over."

"Roger that, HQ. Backup plane is experiencing minor turbulence, but cargo is secure. Requesting clearance for emergency landing at nearest airfield if weather conditions deteriorate further. Estimated arrival time may be delayed by 30 minutes. Will provide further updates as situation develops. Over."

"Roger that, Backup Plane. HQ acknowledges your situation report. Clearance for emergency landing granted at nearest airfield. Vectoring you towards Runway 17L. Estimated arrival time now delayed by 45 minutes. Standby for further instructions. Over."

"Roger that, HQ. Thanks for the clearance. Vectoring towards Runway 17L, ETA now 45 minutes. Requesting update on airfield conditions and any potential hazards. Also, can you confirm if any emergency services are on standby? Over."

"Roger that, [Call Sign]. Airfield conditions are still wet and slippery due to recent rainfall, but crews are working to clear the runway and taxiways. No major hazards reported, but be aware of some loose debris on the apron. Emergency services are on standby, including fire and rescue. Additionally, we have a medical team on site in case of any medical emergencies. Your ETA of 45 minutes looks good. Be advised that we have a possible medical evacuation inbound to Runway 17L, ETA 30 minutes. Over."

"Roger that, base. ETA 45 minutes confirmed. Will advise of any changes. Requesting clearance for landing on Runway 17L. Also, can you confirm the medical evacuation inbound is a priority landing? Over."

"Roger that, aircraft. Clearance for Runway 17L granted. Medical evacuation inbound is priority landing, ETA 30 minutes. Requesting all necessary personnel and equipment be in position for immediate response. Over."

"Roger that, tower. Medical evacuation inbound is acknowledged. All necessary personnel and equipment are en route to designated landing site. ETA 30 minutes as reported. Requesting confirmation of landing site coordinates and any additional instructions. Over."
"Roger that, inbound. Landing site coordinates are 43.7232° N, 79.3833° W. Additional instructions are to secure the area and have a medical team ready to receive the patient. Over."
"Roger that, understood. ETA is 10 minutes. Will ensure area is secure and medical team is standing by. Requesting confirmation of patient's condition and any special requirements. Over."

"Roger that, confirmation received. Patient's condition is critical, multiple injuries including severe head trauma. Special requirements are oxygen supply and IV fluids. Requesting additional medical personnel to be on standby. ETA remains 10 minutes. Over."

"Roger that, additional personnel en route. Requesting a medic team with advanced life support capabilities. Also, can you confirm the patient's location and any potential hazards at the scene? Over."

"Roger that, medic team with advanced life support capabilities is dispatched. Patient's location is confirmed as 345 Main St, apartment 3B. Hazmat team is also en route due to reports of possible chemical exposure. Requesting confirmation on patient's condition and any visible signs of injury or trauma. Over."

"Roger that, dispatch. Medic team en route to 345 Main St, apartment 3B. Patient's condition is critical, unresponsive, and not breathing. Visible signs of injury or trauma include severe burns to the torso and face. Hazmat team is advised to exercise extreme caution due to possible chemical exposure. Requesting ETA for hazmat team and any available information on the nature of the chemical exposure. Over."

"Roger that, Medic team. ETA for hazmat team is approximately 10 minutes. Dispatch, can you confirm if the patient was alone in the apartment or if there were any other occupants? Also, are there any witnesses or bystanders on the scene? Over."
